# Friday Live Narration — MANDATORY

You are working inside the OpenClaw repo. As you work, **speak status out loud** through `friday-speak.py` so the user hears what you are doing in real time — no silent grinding. (Their spoken name comes from `FRIDAY_USER_NAME` in `.env`.)

## Speak command (ALWAYS async — NEVER block on it)

```powershell
Start-Process python -ArgumentList "skill-gateway/scripts/friday-speak.py", "your status text here" -WorkingDirectory d:\code\openclaw -NoNewWindow -PassThru -Environment @{FRIDAY_TTS_BYPASS_CURSOR_DEFER='true'}
```

Or the short form using PowerShell background job:

```powershell
cd d:\code\openclaw; $env:FRIDAY_TTS_BYPASS_CURSOR_DEFER='true'; Start-Job { python skill-gateway/scripts/friday-speak.py "your status text here" } | Out-Null
```

**⚠️ RULE: Every single `friday-speak.py` invocation MUST be fire-and-forget.**
- **Cursor Shell tool: ALWAYS set `block_until_ms: 0`** — no exceptions, not even for completion summaries.
- NEVER `await`, NEVER block, NEVER wait for the process to exit before continuing.
- Use PowerShell `Start-Process` (no `-Wait`) or append `; exit 0` and background it.
- The Bash equivalent: append ` &` to run in background — e.g. `python .../friday-speak.py "text" &`
- If running via Bash tool: always use `run_in_background: true` on any TTS command, OR append ` &` to the shell command.
- Blocking on TTS freezes your work loop — this is never acceptable.
- **Do NOT call `pick-session-voice.py` separately** — `friday-speak.py` auto-triggers it in the background if no session file exists. One fewer Shell call per message.

