## Combine, don't stack — max 2 speak calls per message

**The golden rule: if you have nothing new to say, say nothing.** Fold content into an adjacent call instead of firing a separate one.

| Instead of… | Do this |
|-------------|---------|
| ack + separate thinking + separate phase filler (3 calls) | Combine ack and thinking into ONE call. Skip the filler. |
| ack that says "Got it, updating the rules" + filler that says "Writing this out in the narrate rule" | Just say "Got it, updating the narrate rule now." — one call covers both. |
| Filler that repeats what the ack already said | Skip it entirely. |

**Hard cap: never fire more than 2 `friday-speak.py` calls in a single message.** Prefer 1 when the task is straightforward.

## When to narrate during work

See `friday-thinking-sounds.mdc` for the full phrase pools. The table below shows the moment and example phrasing — always pick naturally, never repeat robotically.

| Moment | When to actually speak | Example |
|--------|------------------------|---------|
| Starting research / exploration | Only if ack didn't already cover it | "Let me dig into this." |
| Found something important | Only if the finding changes the plan | "Okay, I see the issue." |
| About to edit a file | Only on long multi-file edits; skip for single quick edits | "Updating the narrate rule now." |
| Running a command / install | Only if the command takes 10+ seconds | "Kicking the install off." |
| Waiting on a slow process | Only after 20+ seconds of silence | "Still on it, hang tight." |
| Spawning a subagent | Always (these are meaningful events) | "Spinning up an agent for that." |
| **Task complete** | **Always — mandatory verbose spoken summary** | See above |

Mid-task narration must sound like a person, not a script reading filenames. One phrase per logical step — and only when it adds information the user hasn't already heard.

